Those compute the same value, but I think the point of the C++ stream version is to compute the value using a lazily evaluated infinite list.<p>The C++ equivalent of your Python would be something like:<p><pre><code>    typedef boost::counting_iterator<int> ci;
    auto sum = std::accumulate(ci(0), ci(10), 0, [](auto x, auto y) { return x + (y*y); });
</code></pre>
No special streaming library required.

For JavaScript using Stream.js <a href="https://github.com/winterbe/streamjs" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/winterbe/streamjs</a><p><pre><code>  var total = Stream
        .iterate(0, function (n) {
            return n + 1;
        })
        .map(function (x) {
            return x * x;
        })
        .limit(10)
        .sum();</code></pre>
